irmed", "sources": ["SF Competitors__c: iCertis; Sirion Labs", "SF Next_Step__c 05 Nov 2025 (EY pushing Icertis)", "SF Next_Step__c 21 Jul / 01 Aug 2025 (AI clarification)", "Products__c: iContract; Merlin"], "narrative": "Zycus is in a competitive public tender against Icertis (primary, EY-favoured) and Sirion Labs. Competitors__c lists 'iCertis; Sirion Labs', and the Next Step of 05 Nov 2025 confirms 'EY (supporting process) seems to push for Icertis (working with Alliance to mitigate)', a structural disadvantage because the advisor shapes and scores the tender. The Zycus wedge is Merlin (GenAI contract intelligence) tied to MTR's stated GenAI mandate and the scored AI-clarification requirement; Icertis is comparatively rules-based CLM. How we win: make Merlin the strategic centrepiece of the tender response, quantify the AI/automation ROI, and reach the budget owner so the AI case is evaluated as strategic value rather than a feature checkbox, neutralising EY's Icertis lean."}, "identify_pain": {"status": "partial", "sources": ["SF Next_Step__c 03 Mar 2025, 09 Jun 2025", "Task 20 Mar 2026 (Simon Fung, risk / KYC platform need)"], "narrative": "MTR's pain is articulated qualitatively but never quantified. Two threads are consistent across the record: legacy Oracle EBS procurement modules being migrated and a stated mandate to adopt GenAI in procurement ('they want/must start with GenAI use case', 03 Mar 2025), plus a parallel Supply Chain Risk Management / KYC framework need (20 Mar 2026, Simon Fung). The bundling of eAuction and CLM (09 Jun 2025) suggests a broader desire to consolidate procurement tooling. The pain is real enough to drive a formal tender, but no operational metric (contract cycle time, legal-review bottleneck, compliance exposure, cost leakage) and no single pain owner have been captured, which limits the strength of the value story versus Icertis."}, "paper_process": {"status": "partial", "sources": ["Task 30 Jun / 28 Jun 2026 (hkextender portal registration)", "Task 15 Jun 2026 (executed NDA)", "Task 20 Mar 2026 (3rd Party Risk Management / KYC)", "SF Current_Contract_Expiration__c not populated"], "narrative": "Contracting will follow MTR's public-tender framework: submissions run through the www.hkextender.com e-tender portal (registration approved 30 Jun 2026 after an initial rejection on 28 Jun), the mutual NDA was executed on 15 Jun 2026, and a third-party risk-management / KYC requirement is in scope (20 Mar 2026 email from Simon Fung). Formal MSA/SOW redlining, InfoSec review, and any systems-integration deep-dive (Oracle EBS) will follow vendor selection. There is no Current_Contract_Expiration__c populated, so there is no contractual renewal forcing function; the tender timeline itself is the clock. What would create visibility is MTR's published tender schedule and evaluation milestones, which should be extracted from the Q114354 document."}, "economic_buyer": {"status": "gap", "sources": ["Contact Role: Alex Gautier, Decision Maker", "SF Next_Step__c 08 Dec 2025", "Task 14 Jun 2026 Horizon invite to Alex", "No Economic Buyer contact role present"], "narrative": "No economic buyer is engaged. Alex Gautier (General Manager - Procurement & Supply Chain) is the Salesforce Decision Maker and the most senior mapped contact, but there is no record of him joining a call or commercial conversation; outreach to him was limited to Horizon-event invitations (25 Mar and 14 Jun 2026 emails). No budget owner or CFO-level sponsor is named in the contact roles, and the AIS note flags 'not able to identify champion / exec sponsor engagement' (08 Dec 2025). In a public tender the formal budget sits above procurement, so identifying and reaching the budget owner behind Q114354 is a ranked move. What the evidence does show is that procurement (Alex Gautier, Navjot Singh, Lilian Au-Yeung) owns the process today, not that a commercial sponsor has been secured."}, "decision_process": {"status": "partial", "sources": 